1
00:01:05,046 --> 00:01:10,564
# Once a native maiden and a stranger met

2
00:01:10,606 --> 00:01:15,521
# Underneath a blue Tahitian moon

3
00:01:15,566 --> 00:01:18,478
# The stars were in her eyes

4
00:01:18,526 --> 00:01:21,802
# Gardenias in her hair

5
00:01:21,846 --> 00:01:27,159
# And they vowed to care forever

6
00:01:27,206 --> 00:01:32,883
(Muffled) # Then one lonely day
the stranger sailed away

7
00:01:32,926 --> 00:01:36,555
# With a parting kiss that came too soon

8
00:01:37,926 --> 00:01:40,565
# And now the trade winds sigh

9
00:01:40,606 --> 00:01:43,484
# When ships go sailing by... #

10
00:01:43,526 --> 00:01:47,804
<i>(Neville Chamberlain)</i>
<i>This country is at war with Germany.</i>

11
00:01:47,846 --> 00:01:49,916
(Air-raid sirens)

12
00:01:53,046 --> 00:01:57,676
# Once a native maiden and a stranger met

13
00:01:58,326 --> 00:02:02,365
# Underneath a blue Tahitian moon

14
00:02:03,246 --> 00:02:06,318
# The stars were in her eyes

15
00:02:06,366 --> 00:02:09,438
# Gardenias in her hair #

16
00:02:09,486 --> 00:02:12,876
<i>(Man on radio) Down here</i>
<i>on the platform of Piccadilly Tube station</i>

17
00:02:12,926 --> 00:02:16,362
<i>in the heart of London's West End....</i>

18
00:02:16,406 --> 00:02:19,045
<i>Many are bombed out of their homes...</i>

19
00:02:19,086 --> 00:02:22,317
<i>... today of the evacuation</i>
<i>of London's schoolchildren.</i>

20
00:02:24,326 --> 00:02:27,363
<i>... two attacks against London</i>
<i>and Southeast England.</i>

21
00:02:27,406 --> 00:02:30,443
<i>... 200 feet below ground,</i>
<i>but they feel safe here.</i>

22
00:02:30,486 --> 00:02:32,283
# When ships go sailing by

23
00:02:32,326 --> 00:02:36,763
# Underneath a blue Tahitian moon #

24
00:02:42,366 --> 00:02:44,675
(Air-raid siren)

25
00:02:50,086 --> 00:02:51,724
(Quiet voices)

26
00:02:57,446 --> 00:02:59,516
(Man laughs)

27
00:03:06,206 --> 00:03:09,403
(Woman) But you're not a coward.
(Man) I don't want to die.

28
00:03:09,446 --> 00:03:12,085
And why should I? And if I don't,
why should anyone else?

29
00:03:12,126 --> 00:03:14,959
(Woman) Yet, still,
you wouldn't make peace now.

30
00:03:15,006 --> 00:03:18,794
Not now. You wouldn't support that.
You couldn't.

31
00:03:18,846 --> 00:03:21,679
You've only got the one life, Anita. Just the one.

32
00:03:21,726 --> 00:03:22,920
Dylan?

33
00:03:23,926 --> 00:03:25,484
Is it?

34
00:03:26,726 --> 00:03:28,444
Dylan Thomas. It is, isn't it?

35
00:03:28,486 --> 00:03:30,124
Oh, my God.

36
00:03:31,446 --> 00:03:34,643
- You might at least have lifted my veil!
- Oh, my God. Still love me?

37
00:03:34,686 --> 00:03:37,154
- Did I ever?
- Lift the bloody veil, Vera.

38
00:03:40,686 --> 00:03:43,120
Look at you.

39
00:03:43,166 --> 00:03:45,441
Look at you. Not been called up?

40
00:03:45,486 --> 00:03:49,399
Just because I haven't got a uniform.
It's me that puts the heart in the nation.

41
00:03:49,446 --> 00:03:51,357
Ammo factories, I sing in.

42
00:03:51,406 --> 00:03:54,762
- Down the tubes right now.
- I always loved your voice. Always.

43
00:03:54,806 --> 00:03:57,445
- Amongst other things, I loved...
- Don't you come it, Dylan Thomas!

44
00:03:57,486 --> 00:03:59,556
- You haven't changed.
- Course I have, thank God.

45
00:03:59,606 --> 00:04:01,836
You can't. And don't. Not ever.

46
00:04:01,886 --> 00:04:04,400
If you do, I won't let you.

47
00:04:04,446 --> 00:04:06,676
I heard you on the radio.

48
00:04:07,486 --> 00:04:11,115
Like going home, it was, your poems.
Like going back.

49
00:04:12,046 --> 00:04:14,958
- Where's the posh accent from?
- You should've looked me up.

50
00:04:15,006 --> 00:04:16,883
- Should I?
- Mm.

51
00:04:18,566 --> 00:04:22,684
If I can get all my friends to donate
five bob each, this is the plan, see.

52
00:04:22,726 --> 00:04:26,924
If I get them all to do that, I don't have to sell
my soul writing bloody propaganda films.

53
00:04:26,966 --> 00:04:30,242
- I can write my bloody poetry.
- You'd have to join the army.

54
00:04:30,286 --> 00:04:32,925
Grade Three sitting here before you, Vera.

55
00:04:32,966 --> 00:04:36,197
Lungs raddled like a Sunday whore.

56
00:04:38,726 --> 00:04:42,116
So... lend us five bob.

57
00:04:42,966 --> 00:04:46,436
- I'll give you a snout, that's all you'll get.
- Oh. Give us, then.

58
00:04:47,806 --> 00:04:52,084
- Silver's for the lonely, Vera Bera.
- Who says I'm lonely?

59
00:04:52,126 --> 00:04:55,277
- Well, where's the man who'll give you gold?
- That an offer, is it?

60
00:04:55,326 --> 00:04:58,602
- It's always been shares with us.
- You never had anything to share.

61
00:04:58,646 --> 00:05:02,195
Yes, but if I did,
if ever I did, you'd be the first.

62
00:05:02,246 --> 00:05:06,524
There's no folks like home folks.
And folks you've grown up with...

63
00:05:08,606 --> 00:05:10,836
...they're the best of all.

64
00:05:13,166 --> 00:05:15,441
- You win.
- Goody.

65
00:05:20,606 --> 00:05:22,198
Forever and always.

66
00:05:24,726 --> 00:05:26,364
You won't, will you?

67
00:05:26,406 --> 00:05:28,966
- Won't what, lovely?
- Get lost again?

68
00:05:33,686 --> 00:05:35,278
(Train rumbles)

69
00:05:41,126 --> 00:05:42,798
(Soldier) Ta, mate.

70
00:06:01,006 --> 00:06:04,203
- (Wolf-whistling)
- Hello, love!

71
00:06:13,006 --> 00:06:15,520
<i>(Dylan Thomas)</i>
<i>I have longed to move away</i>

72
00:06:15,566 --> 00:06:18,399
<i>From the hissing of the spent lie</i>

73
00:06:18,446 --> 00:06:21,916
<i>And the old terrors' continual cry</i>

74
00:06:21,966 --> 00:06:23,399
<i>Growing more terrible</i>

75
00:06:23,446 --> 00:06:27,325
<i>As the day goes over the hill</i>
<i>into the deep sea</i>

76
00:06:28,126 --> 00:06:30,401
<i>I have longed to move away</i>

77
00:06:30,446 --> 00:06:33,324
<i>From the repetition of salutes</i>

78
00:06:33,366 --> 00:06:35,834
<i>For there are ghosts in the air</i>

79
00:06:35,886 --> 00:06:37,956
<i>And ghostly echoes on paper</i>

80
00:06:38,006 --> 00:06:39,883
(Wolf-whistling)

81
00:06:39,926 --> 00:06:43,521
<i>This is Dylan Thomas</i>
<i>for the BBC Home Service.</i>

82
00:06:43,566 --> 00:06:45,921
(Soldiers calling out)

83
00:06:46,486 --> 00:06:48,442
(Train whistle)

84
00:06:50,406 --> 00:06:53,079
- Hello, darling!
- Where you going?

85
00:06:53,126 --> 00:06:54,479
<i>(Woman) Tension, four hundredweight.</i>

86
00:06:54,526 --> 00:06:58,678
The commentary has to persuade
women to join the balloon defences.

87
00:06:58,726 --> 00:07:02,685
"Shaft a Jerry and maybe one of our
boys will shaft you." That do you?

88
00:07:02,726 --> 00:07:05,957
Your talents really are wasted here, Dylan.

89
00:07:06,006 --> 00:07:09,157
We could have a drink if you like? After.

90
00:07:09,206 --> 00:07:12,357
- Course we could.
- I'm not a bloody dog, Dylan.

91
00:07:12,406 --> 00:07:14,476
It's the brunette, isn't it?

92
00:07:16,566 --> 00:07:21,037
I had a golden childhood, Anita.
And here it is turning up all unexpected.

93
00:07:21,086 --> 00:07:24,442
Now I can't look a golden childhood
in the mouth, can I?

94
00:07:24,486 --> 00:07:26,522
The commentary, please, Dylan.

95
00:07:31,486 --> 00:07:33,442
Myselves

96
00:07:33,486 --> 00:07:35,716
The grievers grieve among the street

97
00:07:35,766 --> 00:07:38,724
Burned to tireless death

98
00:07:38,766 --> 00:07:40,119
A child of a few hours

99
00:07:40,166 --> 00:07:41,485
With its kneading mouth

100
00:07:41,526 --> 00:07:43,801
Charred on the black breast of the grave

101
00:07:43,846 --> 00:07:45,518
The mother dug

102
00:07:45,566 --> 00:07:47,636
And its arms full of fires.

103
00:07:47,686 --> 00:07:52,123
Spare us the bloody tragedy, man.
I need something hopeful here.

104
00:07:54,206 --> 00:07:56,481
The lion once known as Jehovah

105
00:07:56,526 --> 00:07:59,404
- Oh...
- Rose up and cocked its leg over

106
00:07:59,446 --> 00:08:01,402
The lioness roared,
Jehovah had scored

107
00:08:01,446 --> 00:08:03,038
All over the living room sofa

108
00:08:03,086 --> 00:08:05,236
Dylan, I require a commentary.

109
00:08:05,286 --> 00:08:08,437
Dylan! Dylan!

110
00:08:27,046 --> 00:08:28,445
Caitlin?

111
00:08:28,486 --> 00:08:31,603
- You told me you couldn't live without me.
- Where's our son?

112
00:08:31,646 --> 00:08:35,764
Chopped up in little bits and packed
with my knickers in the suitcase.

113
00:08:35,806 --> 00:08:37,683
The police'll be chasing you.

114
00:08:37,726 --> 00:08:40,479
- Don't pretend you want him here.
- There's bombs!

115
00:08:40,526 --> 00:08:45,077
It's nothing to do with bombs.
You don't want him. So I didn't bring him.

116
00:08:46,646 --> 00:08:51,003
I've never been a father before, Cat.
It's not straightforward.

117
00:08:51,046 --> 00:08:54,197
- Still the light of your life, am I?
- In the New Forest, is he?

118
00:08:54,246 --> 00:08:58,205
Why are you asking, Dullun?
You know damn well our son's with my mother.

119
00:08:58,246 --> 00:09:00,282
I love you, Cat.

120
00:09:00,326 --> 00:09:02,715
Give us a fag, then.

121
00:09:02,766 --> 00:09:06,805
I'm out of bleeding fags.
Give my head a good scratch. Please?

122
00:09:09,046 --> 00:09:10,923
Oh, lovely!

123
00:09:10,966 --> 00:09:12,797
- Where are we living?
- Nowhere.

124
00:09:12,846 --> 00:09:15,997
- Ow! Velvet your bloody claws!
- Scratch your own bloody head!

125
00:09:16,046 --> 00:09:17,445
- Come here.
- No.

126
00:09:17,486 --> 00:09:19,158
Kiss me.

127
00:09:24,406 --> 00:09:26,362
(Air-raid siren)

128
00:09:30,286 --> 00:09:33,403
Excuse me.
You dropped your handkerchief.

129
00:09:34,766 --> 00:09:37,360
- No, I didn't.
- Yes, you did. Right there.

130
00:09:38,726 --> 00:09:40,398
It's not mine, sorry.

131
00:09:40,446 --> 00:09:44,155
You're supposed to take the hankie,
I'm supposed to introduce myself,

132
00:09:44,206 --> 00:09:46,879
- buy you a drink.
- I don't want a drink.

133
00:09:49,486 --> 00:09:52,842
- Nice try, though.
- I've never done this before.

134
00:09:52,886 --> 00:09:56,276
No. You've just never
been caught out before.

135
00:10:02,286 --> 00:10:03,844
Hello, darling.

136
00:10:06,366 --> 00:10:10,518
- Sod you, then!
- Oh, dear. Picky, picky, picky.

137
00:10:10,566 --> 00:10:14,445
- You're late.
- I know. It's all her fault.

138
00:10:18,126 --> 00:10:20,924
- Who's your friend?
- Queen of Ireland,

139
00:10:20,966 --> 00:10:25,721
love of my life, mother of my child,
Caitlin Thomas.

140
00:10:27,206 --> 00:10:28,719
Your wife, Dylan?

141
00:10:30,486 --> 00:10:32,556
The one and only.

142
00:10:34,006 --> 00:10:38,955
- He didn't mention...
- Well, he wouldn't, would he?

143
00:10:43,046 --> 00:10:45,480
You made that, didn't you?

144
00:10:47,486 --> 00:10:49,238
I might like you.

145
00:10:49,286 --> 00:10:51,880
Then again, I might not.

146
00:10:53,046 --> 00:10:55,401
I'll await your decision, shall I?

147
00:10:56,286 --> 00:10:58,754
I won't hold my breath, mind.

148
00:11:00,126 --> 00:11:03,960
- Got a mansion we could share?
- Yes. Two little homeless orphans.

149
00:11:04,006 --> 00:11:08,761
- I've only got a room.
- Bugger. Condemned to her sister's.

150
00:11:08,806 --> 00:11:10,876
I'll be having that, sailor boy.

151
00:11:10,926 --> 00:11:14,316
- Needn't let...
- Small matter of a wife?

152
00:11:16,286 --> 00:11:20,757
- Nothing should ever come between us.
- Oh, God, Dylan.

153
00:11:20,806 --> 00:11:23,195
Soul mates, we are, Vera. Always were.

154
00:11:23,246 --> 00:11:27,080
- Don't.
- Stop talking about me.

155
00:11:29,286 --> 00:11:32,915
There's a phone in the hall
where I stay. You know.

156
00:11:34,206 --> 00:11:37,243
If you want me, he's got my number.

157
00:11:41,806 --> 00:11:43,524
What does it mean when she smiles?

158
00:11:45,126 --> 00:11:47,082
I don't know. Never did.

159
00:11:47,126 --> 00:11:49,196
(Knocking)

160
00:11:52,606 --> 00:11:56,281
God help us.
It's the Visigoths from Wales.

161
00:11:57,086 --> 00:11:58,963
Your sister's here.

162
00:11:59,886 --> 00:12:02,719
Back from strangling Germans, then, are you?

163
00:12:02,766 --> 00:12:05,280
Left the other boys playing with their little pistols.

164
00:12:05,326 --> 00:12:08,762
- All ging-gang-gooley and yo-ho-ho.
- (Caitlin giggles)

165
00:12:08,806 --> 00:12:11,081
That what you call poetry, is it?

166
00:12:11,126 --> 00:12:14,118
Look, give us a bed
and we'll stay out from under your feet.

167
00:12:15,486 --> 00:12:23,678
# Maybe it's because I kissed you too much

168
00:12:26,926 --> 00:12:34,082
# Maybe that is why
my kiss means too little

169
00:12:39,366 --> 00:12:50,277
# Maybe with a love so great
and a love so small

170
00:12:51,686 --> 00:13:02,005
# Maybe I'll be left with no love at all

171
00:13:04,406 --> 00:13:15,874
# Maybe I'll be left with no love at all #

172
00:13:23,046 --> 00:13:24,957
(Applause)

173
00:13:27,806 --> 00:13:30,036
(Air-raid siren)

174
00:13:33,486 --> 00:13:37,843
Sometimes I can nurse a single pint
all night. But that's sometimes.

175
00:13:38,846 --> 00:13:40,518
(Slurred) Thank you.

176
00:13:40,766 --> 00:13:43,678
(Soldier) Oh, yeah! I thought it was hilarious.

177
00:13:45,206 --> 00:13:48,596
I'll get them in.
You pay, though, Vera, eh? Fair dos.

178
00:13:48,846 --> 00:13:51,997
- Support the starving poet.
- You are not a bloody poet, Dylan.

179
00:13:52,046 --> 00:13:55,322
You write films about barrage
sodding balloons for your living.

180
00:13:55,366 --> 00:13:56,845
There is a war on.

181
00:13:56,886 --> 00:13:58,877
You know, you're not the man I married.

182
00:13:58,926 --> 00:14:03,158
I did cartwheels in a rubber corset in Peter
Robinson's window when I was hungry.

183
00:14:03,206 --> 00:14:05,720
You were never hungry.
You've always had a man to feed you.

184
00:14:05,766 --> 00:14:08,963
Demonstration purposes it was.
Bet you can't beat that.

185
00:14:09,006 --> 00:14:11,042
Bet I can't.

186
00:14:14,206 --> 00:14:16,197
He's following me.

187
00:14:17,886 --> 00:14:20,241
Don't you have all the luck!

188
00:14:20,286 --> 00:14:21,605
Watch this.

189
00:14:27,366 --> 00:14:29,721
(Men cheer)

190
00:14:33,246 --> 00:14:36,522
- Causing chaos, my lovely.
- What do you need knickers for?

191
00:14:36,566 --> 00:14:39,603
Looking for a good time
with a couple of showgirls?

192
00:14:42,646 --> 00:14:44,841
Three more, please.
Your drinks, chaps.

193
00:14:44,886 --> 00:14:49,801
- Chief stag sees off the competition.
- William Killick.

194
00:14:53,566 --> 00:14:56,797
Vera Phillips.
She's very pleased to meet you.

195
00:14:56,846 --> 00:14:59,121
- Rums all round?
- Mmm, goody!

196
00:14:59,166 --> 00:15:00,679
Four rums, please.

197
00:15:04,406 --> 00:15:07,000
- Do you do cartwheels?
- On the seashore I might.

198
00:15:07,046 --> 00:15:09,685
Ah. I'll take you there.

199
00:15:10,366 --> 00:15:13,915
- You're busy, by the looks of you.
- I could do with some sea air.

200
00:15:14,566 --> 00:15:16,443
I'd like to sit on the beach with you.

201
00:15:17,246 --> 00:15:19,237
Don't you know a brush-off
when you get one?

202
00:15:19,286 --> 00:15:21,322
(Caitlin) Got any smokes?

203
00:15:21,366 --> 00:15:23,641
I enjoyed your show.

204
00:15:23,686 --> 00:15:25,324
- Did you?
- Yes.

205
00:15:27,566 --> 00:15:29,955
- Hey?
- Hay's for horses.

206
00:15:30,006 --> 00:15:31,724
Come for a gallop.

207
00:15:33,046 --> 00:15:36,277
Used to call it busking,
singing in the tube stations.

208
00:15:36,326 --> 00:15:38,794
Coppers used to move you on.

209
00:15:40,206 --> 00:15:42,117
I'll come again, if I may.

210
00:15:43,126 --> 00:15:44,559
Free world.

211
00:15:44,606 --> 00:15:46,801
(Explosion)

212
00:15:54,846 --> 00:15:56,962
(Woman sobs)

213
00:15:59,006 --> 00:16:01,884
(Laughter)

214
00:16:04,086 --> 00:16:08,602
Keeping those rums to yourself?
We're in danger of breaking a thirst.

215
00:16:08,646 --> 00:16:11,683
I don't melt at the sight of a uniform, that's all.

216
00:16:11,726 --> 00:16:16,402
- Sod it. I don't like nosy parkers.
- It was a civil question.

217
00:16:16,446 --> 00:16:19,244
I could have said,
"Are you after my husband?" But I didn't.

218
00:16:19,286 --> 00:16:21,641
(Toilet flushes)

219
00:16:21,686 --> 00:16:25,201
Heartache, that's what I see in a uniform.

220
00:16:25,246 --> 00:16:27,635
I won't love someone
just to have them die on me.

221
00:16:27,686 --> 00:16:30,837
Who's talking about love?
Don't you ever get lonely?

222
00:16:30,886 --> 00:16:34,196
- My work's all I need.
- I used to think I'd be a dancer.

223
00:16:34,246 --> 00:16:36,282
Danced night and day.

224
00:16:38,606 --> 00:16:41,200
I know, you're one of those.

225
00:16:41,246 --> 00:16:44,477
No. No! God!

226
00:16:44,526 --> 00:16:47,199
Not one of those, for God's sake!
Not that I'm averse.

227
00:16:47,246 --> 00:16:50,556
One of the ones
that never got over her first love.

228
00:16:51,566 --> 00:16:54,126
Course I am.

229
00:16:55,886 --> 00:16:57,285
(Air-raid siren)

230
00:16:57,326 --> 00:17:00,124
(Killick) Didn't your mother
teach you any manners?

231
00:17:00,166 --> 00:17:03,203
- All I said...
- You can walk on your own, I know.

232
00:17:03,246 --> 00:17:06,079
Keep your hand on your ha'penny,
that's what my mother taught me.

233
00:17:06,126 --> 00:17:10,119
- I'm not touching you.
- Well, don't look at me either.

234
00:17:10,166 --> 00:17:11,838
Fine.

235
00:17:11,886 --> 00:17:14,195
No, don't do that!

236
00:17:15,566 --> 00:17:18,524
What have you got against me,
Vera Phillips?

237
00:17:19,686 --> 00:17:21,756
